03910nam a22005895i 9780822373681DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20162016ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016018394  a97808223736817 a10.1515/97808223736812doi  a(DE-B1597)554036  a(OCoLC)1170570857  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aN6918b.M288 2016 4aN6918b.M288 2016 7aART0150302bisacsh04a700.94509/042231 aMansoor, Jaleh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarshall Plan Modernism :bItalian Postwar Abstraction and the Beginnings of Autonomia /cJaleh Mansoor. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b26 illustrations, incl. 8 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArt History Publication Initiative00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. LABOR, (WORKERS') AUTONOMY, (ART) WORK -- tONE. THE MONOCHROME IN THE NEOCAPITALIST LABORATORY -- tTWO. LUCIO FONTANA AND THE POLITICS OF THE GESTURE -- tTHREE. ALBERTO BURRI'S PLASTICS AND THE POLITICAL AESTHETICS OF OPACITY -- tFOUR. "WE WANT TO ORGANICIZE DISINTEGRATION" -- tCONCLUSION. "READY-MADE ARTIST AND HUMAN STRIKE," OR FROM AUTONOMY TO STRIKE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on artwork by Lucio Fontana, Alberto Burri, and Piero Manzoni, Jaleh Mansoor demonstrates and reveals how abstract painting, especially the monochrome, broke with fascist-associated futurism and functioned as an index of social transition in postwar Italy. Mansoor refuses to read the singularly striking formal and procedural violence of Fontana's slit canvasses, Burri's burnt and exploded plastics, and Manzoni's "achromes" as metaphors of traumatic memories of World War II. Rather, she locates the motivation for this violence in the history of the medium of painting and in the economic history of postwar Italy. Reconfiguring the relationship between politics and aesthetics, Mansoor illuminates how the monochrome's reemergence reflected Fontana, Burri, and Manzoni's aesthetic and political critique of the Marshall Plan's economic warfare and growing American hegemony. It also anticipated the struggles in Italy's factories, classrooms, and streets that gave rise to Autonomia in the 1960s. Marshall Plan Modernism refigures our understanding of modernist painting as a project about labor and the geopolitics of postwar reconstruction during the Italian Miracle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aArt, AbstractzItaly. 0aArt, Italiany20th century. 0aModernism (Art)zItaly. 7aART / European.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373681zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373681423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373681.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles